    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ab, Af-g, Ao, As, Au). Stands occur in hardpan and volcanic pools on a wide variety of landforms, geomorphic surfaces, and soil series (Barbour et al. 2007b). The <i>Ranunculus bonariensis-Holocarpha virgata</i> association is common in this section, primarily occurring in the southeastern Sacramento Valley in very small, hardpan pools. Three local variants are distinguished by specific taxa: <i>Limnanthes alba, L. douglasii,</i> and <i>Navarretia myersii.</i> The <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Downingia bicornuta</i> association also occurs in the southeastern portion of the section, whereas the <i>Downingia (bicornuta, cuspidata)</i> and the <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Downingia ornatissima</i> associations occur in the northeastern portion of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Go-p). S. Smith (1998b) described a <i>Downingia bicornuta</i> type on flat, broad volcanic valley bottoms and backwater channels with rather different species composition with <i>Damasonium californicum, Eryngium alismifolium,</i> and <i>Eleocharis quinqueflora.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-b). Stands occur in hardpan and volcanic pools on low-terrace, highterrace, mudflow, and volcanic landforms with a wide variety of geomorphic surfaces and soils series (Barbour et al. 2007b, Klein et al. 2007). The <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Downingia bicornuta</i> association occurs in small hardpan and occasionally volcanic pools. The <i>Downingia (bicornuta, cuspidata)</i> association exists only in the northern portion of the section in usually large, volcanic pools. Two variants are based on the presence of the rare taxa: <i>Orcuttia tenuis</i> and <i>O. pilosa.</i> The <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Downingia ornatissima</i> association is common in the northern subsection in small hardpan pools. The <i>Eryngium (vaseyi, castrense)</i> type occurs on a variety of surfaces with smaller pool sizes.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Vernal pools in cismontane California are depleted severely in number and extent. Threats are primarily from loss of habitat due to conversion to agriculture, development, and roads. Threats also include invasion and competition by non-native plants, such as <i>Erodium </i>spp., <i>Hordeum </i>spp., <i>Leontodon taraxacoides, Lolium perenne, </i>and <i>Lythrum hyssopifolia, </i>commonly found in this alliance. A number of authors have investigated grazing practices as management tools in vernal pools to decrease competition of non-native plants, and ecologists have denoted the importance of conserving and restoring the vegetation complexes found in vernal pools (see Treatment of Vernal Pools discussion). </div>
</div>

    

    

